<h2>
    Stocked vs Wild Trout in Oregon Waters
</h2>
<ul>
    <li>
        <strong>Stocked Trout</strong>: Raised in hatcheries and released into lakes and rivers. Usually marked with a clipped adipose fin.
    </li>
    <li>
        <strong>Wild Trout</strong>: Naturally born in rivers. Often must be released (check local regs).
    </li>
</ul>
<p>
    Fishing for both is rewarding, but wild trout provide a special challenge and should be handled with care.
</p>
<h2>
   Top Lakes for Trout Fishing Near Salem
</h2>
<h3>
    Detroit Lake
</h3>
<p>
    A major reservoir east of Salem, Detroit Lake is stocked regularly and offers excellent bank and boat fishing for rainbow trout. Early summer and fall are especially productive.
</p>
<h3>
    Silverton Reservoir
</h3>
<p>
    Just 30 minutes away, this reservoir is stocked with rainbow trout and offers kayak and bank access. It's a great location for beginner fly fishing too.
</p>
<h3>
    Walling Pond &amp; Walter Wirth Lake
</h3>
<p>
    Both located in Salem city limits, these small urban lakes are part of the <strong>“Oregon Fishing in the City”</strong> program. They're stocked regularly and perfect for family outings or a quick lunchtime cast.
</p>
<h2>
    Best Rivers and Creeks for Trout Fishing Near Salem
</h2>
<h3>
   North Santiam River
</h3>
<p>
    One of the best rivers in the region for rainbow and summer steelhead, the upper reaches (above Stayton) are productive for fly and spin fishing. Look for riffles, tailouts, and shady pools.
</p>
<h3>
    Little North Fork Santiam
</h3>
<p>
    A pristine tributary with wild cutthroat and rainbow trout. Fly anglers enjoy dry fly action in summer. Wading is easy and the water is ultra-clear—perfect for sight fishing.
</p>
<h3>
    Willamette River Tributaries
</h3>
<p>
    Small streams feeding the Willamette hold surprisingly good numbers of trout, especially cutthroat. These creeks require stealth and light gear.
</p>

