<h2>
    Trout Fishing Techniques and Gear Essentials
</h2>
<h3>
    Fly Fishing
</h3>
<ul>
    <li>
        <strong>Dry Flies</strong>: Elk Hair Caddis, Parachute Adams
    </li>
    <li>
        <strong>Nymphs</strong>: Hare’s Ear, Pheasant Tail
    </li>
    <li>
        <strong>Streamers</strong>: Woolly Bugger, Zonkers
    </li>
</ul>
<p>
    Use 4–5 weight rods with floating or intermediate lines for most local waters.
</p>
<h3>
    Spin Fishing
</h3>
<ul>
    <li>
        <strong>Lures</strong>: Rooster Tails, Panther Martins, Kastmasters
    </li>
    <li>
        <strong>Bait</strong>: PowerBait, worms, and salmon eggs (in stocked areas)
    </li>
</ul>
<p>
    Use light spinning rods with 4–6 lb test for best results.
</p>
<h2>
    Local Hatcheries and Stocking Programs
</h2>
<p>
    Oregon’s <strong>Department of Fish and Wildlife (ODFW)</strong> stocks thousands of trout annually. Popular hatcheries near Salem include:
</p>
<ul>
    <li>
        <strong>Marion Forks Hatchery</strong>
    </li>
    <li>
        <strong>Minto Fish Hatchery</strong>
    </li>
</ul>
<p>
    Check stocking schedules at myodfw.com to plan your trips around fresh plants.
</p>
<h2>
   Trout Fishing with Kids and Families
</h2>
<p>
    Urban ponds like <strong>Walling Pond</strong>, <strong>Walter Wirth Lake</strong>, and <strong>Silverton Reservoir</strong> are ideal for families. Tips for success:
</p>
<ul>
    <li>
        Use simple bobber rigs.
    </li>
    <li>
        Go during stocking weeks.
    </li>
    <li>
        Bring snacks, sunscreen, and a folding chair!
    </li>
</ul>
