<h2>
    License and Regulation Overview
</h2>
<p>
    To legally fish for trout in Oregon, you’ll need:
</p>
<ul>
    <li>
        <strong>Oregon Angling License</strong> (required for anglers 12+)
    </li>
    <li>
        <strong>Harvest Tag</strong> (not needed for trout unless specifically noted)
    </li>
    <li>
        <strong>Bag Limits</strong>: Generally 5 trout per day in stocked lakes; wild trout often catch-and-release only.
    </li>
</ul>
<h2>
    Trout Fishing Tips from Local Experts
</h2>
<ol>
    <li>
        <strong>Fish early or late</strong>—especially in summer heat.
    </li>
    <li>
        <strong>Use small gear</strong>—light line, small hooks, and subtle colors work best.
    </li>
    <li>
        <strong>Read the water</strong>—look for current breaks, submerged rocks, and shaded pools.
    </li>
    <li>
        <strong>Follow the stocking schedule</strong>—your best chances are within 3–5 days of a trout plant.
    </li>
    <li>
        <strong>Be stealthy</strong>—in clear streams, trout spook easily.
    </li>
</ol>
